<para id="fs-idm447646896"><emphasis effect="bold">Anti-Jewish cartoon, 1890</emphasis></para><figure id="BRI_APUSH_09_06_Immig3" class="full-width">
<media id="fs-idm460655792" alt="The cartoon shows a wall around America. Uncle Sam stands in the doorway, holding his nose and blocking the entrance of the Jewish immigrant. The caption at the bottom of the cartoon reads “The Stranger at our Gate.” The emigrant says, “Can I come in?” Uncle Sam says, “I ‘spose you can; there’s no law to keep you out.”">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/BRI_APUSH_09_06_Immig3.jpg"/>
</media>
<caption>A stereotyped Jewish immigrant is carrying bags that read “poverty,” “disease,” “sabbath desecration,” “anarchy,” and “superstition” as he attempts to enter the United States through a gate that reads “United States of America. Admittance Free. Walk in!”</caption>
</figure>
